WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.280 --> 00:00:02.000
Previously on Prison Break:

2
00:00:02.080 --> 00:00:04.680
It's the only building sitting
on top of those tunnels.

3
00:00:04.680 --> 00:00:07.480
All we gotta do is get in there--
on PI--

4
00:00:07.560 --> 00:00:09.080
and dig ourselves an onramp.

5
00:00:09.200 --> 00:00:10.240
I'm gonna find out. you know.

6
00:00:10.240 --> 00:00:11.760
what it is you're
doing up there.

7
00:00:12.440 --> 00:00:16.080
If we talked about who had motive to
kill Terrence. we'd be here all day.

8
00:00:16.200 --> 00:00:17.520
Have anything to
do with EcoField?

9
00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:20.040
Do the math. CEO of a corporation
gets indicted for fraud.

10
00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:22.600
investors start losing money.
Lots of money.

11
00:00:22.720 --> 00:00:24.800
You call Nick Savrinn.
works for Project Justice.

12
00:00:24.920 --> 00:00:25.880
They're here.

13
00:00:26.360 --> 00:00:27.400
Who's here?

14
00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:30.480
LJ? LJ?!

15
00:00:30.760 --> 00:00:31.840
You gotta come get me.

16
00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:34.600
We can't. okay. We're not in Chicago.
You have to come to us.

17
00:00:34.600 --> 00:00:36.040
First of the month
is coming up. John.

18
00:00:36.120 --> 00:00:37.200
Yeah. so?

19
00:00:37.280 --> 00:00:40.160
Checked my balance online.
it's looking seriously deficient.

20
00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:42.760
Apparently. Fibonacci's
coming up for air again.

21
00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:46.960
And if he testifies at that hearing.
a lot of people are going down.

22
00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:48.680
including me.

23
00:00:48.800 --> 00:00:52.040
Listen. there. uh.
there's been a restructuring.

24
00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:53.880
This comes from Philly himself.

25
00:00:53.960 --> 00:00:55.800
So I'm the man in here now.

26
00:00:57.920 --> 00:00:59.520
What the hell are you doing?

27
00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:02.520
Uh-oh. We got a problem.

28
00:01:03.280 --> 00:01:05.480
Bellick. What's going on?

29
00:01:05.560 --> 00:01:08.160
That's PI. I run it.

30
00:01:08.840 --> 00:01:10.480
Not anymore you don't.

31
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:18.074
Support us and become VIP member 
to remove all ads from www.OpenSubtitles.org

32
00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:13.680
Bellick.

33
00:02:15.120 --> 00:02:16.160
Hey. boss.

34
00:02:16.240 --> 00:02:17.800
Check that volume. inmate.

35
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:21.640
We been doing business too long.
We can fix this thing. right?

36
00:02:22.400 --> 00:02:23.640
Let's get something clear.

37
00:02:24.040 --> 00:02:27.000
You and I haven't done crap.
Falzone's the one been paying me.

38
00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:28.520
Falzone is just an envelope.

39
00:02:28.640 --> 00:02:30.760
You've been doing business
with me face-to-face.

40
00:02:30.760 --> 00:02:34.280
You think I like getting
piss thrown at me? Spit on?

41
00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:37.760
These other chumps might do
it for the 40 grand a year

42
00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:40.040
and the little blue uniform.
but I'm not that dumb.

43
00:02:40.120 --> 00:02:44.160
Falzone's envelope is the only reason
I come through that fence every day.

44
00:02:44.280 --> 00:02:45.720
And it's the only reason

45
00:02:45.800 --> 00:02:48.280
I'm gonna keep coming
through that fence

46
00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:51.360
until I have enough money to
buy that house on Lake Gray.

47
00:02:51.560 --> 00:02:53.560
I'm thinking early
retirement. John.

48
00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:55.120
and you're
interfering with that.

49
00:02:55.120 --> 00:02:57.200
Hey. boss.
just give me some time.

50
00:02:57.600 --> 00:03:00.080
and I can match whatever
Falzone's paying you.

51
00:03:00.200 --> 00:03:03.360
You're out of business.
Get used to it.

52
00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:05.840
Hey. boss. Boss!

53
00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:27.120
They're gonna find it.

54
00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:30.760
The longer they're in there.
the sooner they're gonna find it.

55
00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:32.400
Then we got to
get back in there.

56
00:03:33.160 --> 00:03:35.400
I'm gonna say something
crazy to you right now.

57
00:03:35.480 --> 00:03:36.920
Surprise. surprise.

58
00:03:37.120 --> 00:03:39.880
I don't give a damn
about Fibonacci anymore.

59
00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:41.520
You're right. That is crazy.

60
00:03:41.720 --> 00:03:44.880
Because I got bigger things to
think about. like survival.

61
00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:47.640
You see.
I'm kinda short on friends in here.

62
00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:49.280
in case you haven't noticed.

63
00:03:51.760 --> 00:03:54.280
I need to get out. Right now.

64
00:03:54.480 --> 00:03:55.920
While I still got my life.

65
00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:57.920
Then why are we talking
about Fibonacci?

66
00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:00.520
Well. the only way I
can get that room back

67
00:04:00.520 --> 00:04:02.800
is if I can prove to Falzone
that I'm still worthy.

68
00:04:02.800 --> 00:04:04.840
that I still got
what it takes. Yeah?

69
00:04:04.920 --> 00:04:06.360
And the only way I can do that
is if I can give him Fibonacci.

70
00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:07.800
Interesting.

71
00:04:08.280 --> 00:04:12.200
You see. this is not a "me
versus you" thing anymore.

72
00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:15.000
This is us.
an "us" thing. all right?

73
00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:17.000
It's us for the escape.

74
00:04:17.080 --> 00:04:17.760
Is it?

75
00:04:17.960 --> 00:04:20.840
Or is this about you getting
back in good with the mob again?

76
00:04:20.840 --> 00:04:22.760
That life is over for me. Fish.

77
00:04:22.960 --> 00:04:24.760
I mean. they clipped my wings.

78
00:04:25.240 --> 00:04:26.880
They want me to rot in here.

79
00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:29.560
So I got no allegiance
to them anymore.

80
00:04:29.680 --> 00:04:31.880
Yet you still want
to do them a favor.

81
00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:36.760
Falzone is desperate.

82
00:04:37.160 --> 00:04:40.880
You see. if Fibonacci testifies in
front of the congress next month.

83
00:04:40.960 --> 00:04:43.000
Falzone's going to
go down in flames.

84
00:04:43.360 --> 00:04:47.400
But if we give him Fibonacci.
he will give us anything--

85
00:04:47.800 --> 00:04:51.320
anything-- including
that very special room.

86
00:04:53.080 --> 00:04:54.880
What do you say. Fish?

87
00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:13.600
Give him up.

88
00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:14.920
If I do. they'll kill him.

89
00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:16.080
Maybe he deserves it.

90
00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:18.200
That's just it. he doesn't.

91
00:05:18.760 --> 00:05:21.080
Who is this guy?
You told me he was Mafia.

92
00:05:21.160 --> 00:05:23.760
He was working for the Mafia.
he just didn't know it.

93
00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:26.840
Otto Fibonacci is...

94
00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:28.920
is just like you.

95
00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:30.640
An innocent man.

96
00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:33.840
Caught in the wrong
place at the wrong time.

97
00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:36.680
What are you doing...?
You know...

98
00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:38.520
I didn't steal from you. John.

99
00:05:39.400 --> 00:05:42.440
He was middle management at
one of Abruzzi's warehouses.

100
00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:46.080
Just a normal guy.
Working class. religious.

101
00:05:47.040 --> 00:05:48.120
I didn't steal from you. John!

102
00:05:48.120 --> 00:05:51.080
Hey. Nicky. Nicky. Nicky. Nicky.
Shh. shh. shh.

103
00:05:52.240 --> 00:05:54.240
What did I tell
you about talking?

104
00:05:54.840 --> 00:05:56.080
John. please.

105
00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:00.880
John. please! No!

106
00:06:03.560 --> 00:06:05.960
And somebody that couldn't
turn his back on murder.

107
00:06:06.800 --> 00:06:09.800
He realized that Abruzzi and Falzone--
the men he worked for--

108
00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:11.120
were killers.

109
00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:13.040
And he had the key to
all their dealings.

110
00:06:13.160 --> 00:06:15.080
Things that could put
them away for life.

111
00:06:15.080 --> 00:06:17.440
And now he's in witness
protection for life.

112
00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:21.120
The judge asked him why he was coming
forward with all this information.

113
00:06:21.480 --> 00:06:24.920
He said it was because he thought
it was the right thing to do.

114
00:06:25.240 --> 00:06:27.440
What's the right thing
to do now. Michael?

115
00:06:27.640 --> 00:06:29.240
I don't know.

116
00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:31.480
But if I don't give him up.

117
00:06:31.920 --> 00:06:34.320
this whole thing's over.

118
00:06:36.080 --> 00:06:40.000
What you're telling me is. if...
if I'm to live...

119
00:06:42.760 --> 00:06:45.080
A good man has to die.

120
00:07:22.400 --> 00:07:23.520
Kellerman.

121
00:07:23.720 --> 00:07:25.560
You're in the
place we discussed?

122
00:07:25.640 --> 00:07:26.520
Yes.

123
00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:29.760
I'm still not exactly sure
why we're here. but...

124
00:07:29.880 --> 00:07:32.080
A friend of mine should
be along there shortly.

125
00:07:32.160 --> 00:07:33.040
A friend?

126
00:07:33.120 --> 00:07:35.320
Just to see where
you are with things.

127
00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:37.040
I think we're clear on
where we are with things.

128
00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:38.480
Everything's under control.

129
00:07:38.680 --> 00:07:41.960
Nothing is going to affect tomorrow.
if that's what you're worried about.

130
00:07:42.040 --> 00:07:43.880
I'm not worried about tomorrow.

131
00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:47.040
My friend is a problem solver.
that's all.

132
00:07:47.120 --> 00:07:50.280
He's there at your
disposal if you need him.

133
00:07:50.400 --> 00:07:52.000
Do me a favor.

134
00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:55.360
Make him feel like
part of the team. hmm?

135
00:07:55.680 --> 00:07:57.120
Talk soon.

136
00:08:00.640 --> 00:08:02.360
- What?
- She's bringing someone in.

137
00:08:02.760 --> 00:08:03.800
What does that mean?

138
00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:05.640
Something in her tone changed.

139
00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:07.640
You think she knows
about the kid?

140
00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:09.760
We don't know that.

141
00:08:10.520 --> 00:08:12.080
We shouldn't have lied.

142
00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:13.400
Shouldn't have told
her we had the kid.

143
00:08:13.400 --> 00:08:14.960
What is it you
don't understand?

144
00:08:15.120 --> 00:08:18.000
We tell her that kid got away.
you and I. we are not here right now.

145
00:08:18.120 --> 00:08:21.480
I swear to God.
it just get deeper and deeper.

146
00:08:21.560 --> 00:08:22.800
What is that supposed to mean?

147
00:08:22.800 --> 00:08:24.160
It means if I'd have known

148
00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:25.760
that this is how this whole
thing was gonna turn out.

149
00:08:25.760 --> 00:08:27.520
I would've gotten some
crap job with the feds.

150
00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:32.120
Push pencils. drink coffee all day long
behind a desk. God. that sounds good.

151
00:08:33.240 --> 00:08:37.080
Keep talking like that. I'm gonna be
forced to put a bullet in your head.

152
00:08:40.360 --> 00:08:44.680
As for her friend.
whoever that is.

153
00:08:44.760 --> 00:08:46.800
we find out what he wants.
we play nice.

154
00:08:47.080 --> 00:08:48.680
we deal with it accordingly.

155
00:08:51.880 --> 00:08:53.480
Michael. you better see this.

156
00:09:00.480 --> 00:09:01.560
Hey. Jersey.

157
00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:03.640
Putting that carpet
in the guard's room?

158
00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:04.800
Yeah. Think so.

159
00:09:05.080 --> 00:09:06.440
Mm-hmm. When?

160
00:09:06.640 --> 00:09:08.640
Got to tear up the
old stuff first.

161
00:09:08.840 --> 00:09:12.680
Soon as we're done with that.
Tonight. Tomorrow maybe.

162
00:09:12.960 --> 00:09:14.480
They're gonna find it. bro.

163
00:09:14.600 --> 00:09:16.240
They're gonna find the hole.

164
00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:17.960
We got to do something.

165
00:09:29.920 --> 00:09:31.960
Linc. Chow.

166
00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:38.280
What's this?

167
00:09:38.360 --> 00:09:42.520
It's for. uh. you know.
your last meal.

168
00:09:42.800 --> 00:09:44.320
Write down what you want.

169
00:09:51.400 --> 00:09:53.520
Linc. you gotta
write something down.

170
00:09:54.480 --> 00:09:55.640
I don't gotta do nothing.

171
00:09:59.480 --> 00:10:01.200
You don't fill it out.

172
00:10:01.400 --> 00:10:04.360
all they're gonna give you is
what's on chow for that day.

173
00:10:04.480 --> 00:10:05.240
So?

174
00:10:05.800 --> 00:10:09.720
You don't want that for your last meal.
do you. man? Hmm?

175
00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:19.800
In case you think of something.

176
00:10:36.120 --> 00:10:37.160
Hey. eye-tie.

177
00:10:41.400 --> 00:10:44.080
Something you need
there. rughead?

178
00:10:45.120 --> 00:10:46.960
Yeah. a job. man.

179
00:10:47.520 --> 00:10:50.480
Why don't you hit the DQ down
the street. We aren't hiring.

180
00:10:51.160 --> 00:10:53.480
I'll put a hundred in your kick.
every month.

181
00:10:55.200 --> 00:10:56.720
You want to pay me to work?

182
00:10:57.200 --> 00:10:59.120
Man. I've been in the
kitchen for eight months.

183
00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:00.480
I scrub one more tray.

184
00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:02.760
I'm gonna go J-Cat.
you know what I'm saying?

185
00:11:02.960 --> 00:11:04.680
Hey! Fiorello. how about it?

186
00:11:04.880 --> 00:11:05.360
Eh...

187
00:11:06.880 --> 00:11:08.440
One fifty.

188
00:11:10.360 --> 00:11:12.280
Sign me up then. baby.

189
00:11:21.560 --> 00:11:23.200
I was thinking
about what you said.

190
00:11:24.640 --> 00:11:26.560
That it's not a "me
versus you" thing.

191
00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:28.200
It's an "us" thing.

192
00:11:29.920 --> 00:11:31.160
That's right.

193
00:11:31.240 --> 00:11:33.080
How far are you willing
to go with that?

194
00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:34.600
As far as I have to.

195
00:11:34.800 --> 00:11:36.640
Then set up a
meeting with Falzone.

196
00:11:37.400 --> 00:11:38.920
I want to talk to him directly.

197
00:11:39.800 --> 00:11:43.720
Falzone doesn't talk to
guys like you directly.

198
00:11:44.120 --> 00:11:47.160
If he wants Fibonacci.
he's gonna have to.

199
00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:52.920
No. no! No. you heard me right.

200
00:11:53.040 --> 00:11:55.240
You're telling me this kid
is gonna give up Fibonacci?

201
00:11:55.240 --> 00:11:56.680
- You're sure?
- Definitely--

202
00:11:56.760 --> 00:12:00.040
Only one thing.
He wants to meet with you directly.

203
00:12:00.120 --> 00:12:03.480
Son of a bitch.
you actually did something right. John.

204
00:12:03.560 --> 00:12:04.360
That's good.

205
00:12:04.440 --> 00:12:07.680
Guess I'm gonna have to call off
those guys I hired to shank you.

206
00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:11.440
- That was a joke. John.
- Funny.

207
00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.520
Good. I'll come out
there this afternoon.

208
00:12:14.600 --> 00:12:16.920
And John...
If I come all the way out there.

209
00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:18.840
and this turns out to
be a waste of my time.

210
00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:20.440
I'm gonna castrate you.

211
00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:23.160
I hope you understand that.
Be well. my friend.

212
00:12:23.600 --> 00:12:24.560
I love you. too.

213
00:12:31.120 --> 00:12:35.040
He's coming.
Don't mess this up.

214
00:13:03.800 --> 00:13:04.680
Hello?

215
00:13:05.040 --> 00:13:06.120
It's me.

216
00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:09.160
I know.
I saw "Inmate" on the caller ID.

217
00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:12.240
Remember when I said I might
be calling you on Fibonacci?

218
00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:13.200
Yes.

219
00:13:13.600 --> 00:13:17.040
Well... it's time.

220
00:13:17.800 --> 00:13:19.320
You seem distracted.

221
00:13:19.720 --> 00:13:21.560
Got a lot on my mind. I guess.

222
00:13:21.720 --> 00:13:22.680
Yeah?

223
00:13:23.480 --> 00:13:26.640
Got anything to do with the
people who took these toes?

224
00:13:26.720 --> 00:13:29.200
- Nice flowers.
- Right.

225
00:13:29.680 --> 00:13:31.440
Do we have an admirer?

226
00:13:31.520 --> 00:13:32.960
They're from my father.

227
00:13:33.040 --> 00:13:35.560
Ah... what's the occasion?

228
00:13:36.040 --> 00:13:37.280
It's my birthday.

229
00:13:37.360 --> 00:13:38.600
- Today?
- Mm-hmm.

230
00:13:39.960 --> 00:13:42.560
- Happy birthday.
- Thank you.

231
00:13:44.560 --> 00:13:47.360
- Okay.
- Hmm.

232
00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:49.560
Nothing.

233
00:13:49.920 --> 00:13:53.280
Birthdays aren't usually a sore subject.
that's all.

234
00:13:53.760 --> 00:13:56.560
Unless the celebrant
is feeling her age.

235
00:13:56.640 --> 00:13:59.240
which I don't see
how you could be.

236
00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:04.040
I'm 29 years old. Michael.
I'm not feeling my age.

237
00:14:04.240 --> 00:14:05.840
It's just that out of
those 29 birthdays.

238
00:14:05.840 --> 00:14:10.160
my father has actually managed to
see me on precisely... six of them.

239
00:14:10.360 --> 00:14:14.000
So... I get flowers instead.

240
00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:17.280
Flowers that end up dead and
in the trash a week later.

241
00:14:18.600 --> 00:14:20.520
That sounded bitter. huh?

242
00:14:21.120 --> 00:14:22.360
Kind of.

243
00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:23.880
It's not that big a deal.

244
00:14:24.080 --> 00:14:26.080
You are all set.
I will see you tomorrow.

245
00:14:26.080 --> 00:14:26.760
Okay.

246
00:14:29.920 --> 00:14:32.120
I'm sorry you feel that way.

247
00:14:33.360 --> 00:14:34.640
About the flowers. I mean.

248
00:14:42.280 --> 00:14:44.880
Hey! Somebody get on this.
I want these in the other room.

249
00:14:44.880 --> 00:14:45.960
I got it. boss.

250
00:14:46.240 --> 00:14:48.040
Chill. lily white. I got it.

251
00:15:10.600 --> 00:15:12.680
Come on.
I know you're around here somewhere.

252
00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:44.240
He's not doing well. is he?

253
00:15:44.840 --> 00:15:46.440
Just lost his mother.

254
00:15:47.520 --> 00:15:50.200
Ten days from now.
he loses his father.

255
00:15:58.640 --> 00:15:59.960
How are you holding up?

256
00:16:04.760 --> 00:16:06.200
You know. I. uh...

257
00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:09.680
I sort of get what you're
going through here. LJ.

258
00:16:12.440 --> 00:16:15.040
No disrespect.
but I don't know that you do.

259
00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:18.000
No. with my dad.

260
00:16:18.600 --> 00:16:21.960
I was in the same spot
when I was your age.

261
00:16:22.040 --> 00:16:23.760
He was in prison.

262
00:16:24.040 --> 00:16:26.160
And like your dad.
he was innocent.

263
00:16:27.040 --> 00:16:28.160
What happened?

264
00:16:28.480 --> 00:16:31.040
I mean. you know. at the end.

265
00:16:31.240 --> 00:16:34.400
What I hope happens here.
He got exonerated.

266
00:16:34.880 --> 00:16:37.480
What'd they say he did?

267
00:16:37.560 --> 00:16:39.200
A lot of bad things.

268
00:16:39.960 --> 00:16:41.320
They weren't true.

269
00:16:41.520 --> 00:16:43.240
And we proved that.

270
00:16:43.600 --> 00:16:46.320
Every day.
every day was a lost cause...

271
00:16:46.400 --> 00:16:47.720
but we kept fighting.

272
00:16:47.840 --> 00:16:49.960
I mean.
what else are you gonna do?

273
00:16:50.120 --> 00:16:52.840
When you love somebody.
you gonna let them go out like that?

274
00:16:52.840 --> 00:16:54.360
So you fight.

275
00:16:54.440 --> 00:16:55.880
You keep fighting.

276
00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:57.520
You never give up.

277
00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:01.840
We're gonna beat this thing.

278
00:17:02.800 --> 00:17:03.760
Okay?

279
00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:14.000
- Hello.
- Hello.

280
00:17:14.480 --> 00:17:15.760
You were expecting me.

281
00:17:15.840 --> 00:17:17.560
A mutual friend arranged the...

282
00:17:17.680 --> 00:17:18.320
Yes.

283
00:17:19.200 --> 00:17:21.120
- You mind if I...
- Please.

284
00:17:22.640 --> 00:17:24.360
Hey. how are...

285
00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:29.760
I'm sorry.
I didn't get your name.

286
00:17:29.760 --> 00:17:30.520
Quinn.

287
00:17:31.560 --> 00:17:33.960
Mr. Quinn.
mind telling us what you're doing here?

288
00:17:34.160 --> 00:17:38.760
You can probably tell just by looking
at me. I'm not a wave-making sort.

289
00:17:38.960 --> 00:17:41.720
Just think of me
as a supervisor.

290
00:17:41.840 --> 00:17:44.600
here to make sure things are
under control. as we approach.

291
00:17:44.720 --> 00:17:46.160
you know. the big event.

292
00:17:46.160 --> 00:17:48.640
I wasn't aware that things
are out of control.

293
00:17:48.720 --> 00:17:51.040
You'd be the one that would know.
wouldn't you?

294
00:17:55.440 --> 00:17:57.840
Well. the reason I'm here

295
00:17:57.960 --> 00:18:01.120
is because there's a discrepancy
between what you know.

296
00:18:01.200 --> 00:18:03.040
and what you've said
to the vice president.

297
00:18:03.040 --> 00:18:05.520
The lawyers you tried to blow up.
they're still running around.

298
00:18:05.520 --> 00:18:06.680
healthy as thoroughbreds.

299
00:18:06.680 --> 00:18:08.600
You know it. I know it.

300
00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:10.600
Same thing goes with the kid.

301
00:18:10.800 --> 00:18:12.720
Who you were silly enough

302
00:18:12.920 --> 00:18:15.600
to tell the old lady that you
were actually in possession of.

303
00:18:15.600 --> 00:18:18.640
Everything that I'm saying
is boiling down to this.

304
00:18:18.840 --> 00:18:23.240
You got to hand the reins over to me
now. so that I can save your ass.

305
00:18:28.720 --> 00:18:29.400
First of all...

306
00:18:31.800 --> 00:18:33.320
No! No!

307
00:18:33.720 --> 00:18:36.320
See? Now you made
me make a wave.

308
00:18:38.320 --> 00:18:41.280
You and your partner are off
the job until further notice.

309
00:18:41.400 --> 00:18:42.520
That doesn't come from me.

310
00:18:42.520 --> 00:18:46.080
doesn't come from the White House.
it comes from the company. understand?

311
00:18:55.960 --> 00:18:58.640
Your proximal and middle
phalanx are broken.

312
00:18:58.760 --> 00:19:00.960
Ice it for 45 minutes.
then splint it--

313
00:19:00.960 --> 00:19:02.400
that's what a doctor
would tell you to do.

314
00:19:02.480 --> 00:19:04.800
so you don't need
to go see one.

315
00:19:22.720 --> 00:19:24.720
EcoField's SEC filings?

316
00:19:24.840 --> 00:19:26.160
Terrence Steadman was murdered

317
00:19:26.280 --> 00:19:29.160
so the information from his indictment
wouldn't be made public. right?

318
00:19:29.160 --> 00:19:30.960
Sure. but since it never
saw the light of day.

319
00:19:30.960 --> 00:19:33.280
we have no way of knowing what
they were trying to cover up.

320
00:19:33.280 --> 00:19:35.760
Steadman's wife said there were
hundreds of millions of dollars

321
00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:37.400
at stake if her
husband went down.

322
00:19:37.480 --> 00:19:40.760
so I figure we follow the money.
and see where it takes us.

323
00:19:40.840 --> 00:19:43.520
$109 million. $212 million...

324
00:19:43.640 --> 00:19:46.040
Over half a billion dollars
that I've found so far

325
00:19:46.120 --> 00:19:49.480
in federal grants to EcoField
for alternative fuel research.

326
00:19:49.560 --> 00:19:51.200
That is a hell of
a lot of money.

327
00:19:51.280 --> 00:19:54.160
But for what? Not only did the
company never make a profit.

328
00:19:54.280 --> 00:19:56.560
As far as I could tell.
they never made anything.

329
00:19:56.680 --> 00:19:59.840
No fuel cells. no patents.
no findings-- nothing.

330
00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:02.120
So EcoField was a sham.
it was a cover?

331
00:20:02.440 --> 00:20:04.440
Question is. for what?

332
00:20:16.240 --> 00:20:16.800
Philly.

333
00:20:20.560 --> 00:20:21.720
Sit down. kid.

334
00:20:27.840 --> 00:20:31.000
So... Fibonacci.

335
00:20:31.760 --> 00:20:33.880
- How'd you find him?
- Did my homework.

336
00:20:37.320 --> 00:20:39.720
You get elliptical with
me for one more second.

337
00:20:39.920 --> 00:20:43.560
and I will cancel you.
You understand me?

338
00:20:43.760 --> 00:20:45.120
Give it up. Fish.

339
00:20:47.200 --> 00:20:49.520
Before someone's transferred to the U.S.
Marshall Service

340
00:20:49.520 --> 00:20:52.480
to be placed in Witness Protection.
they're guarded

341
00:20:52.600 --> 00:20:57.760
by a local sheriff from the county
where the trial will take place.

342
00:20:59.480 --> 00:21:01.200
Sheriff Solomon. please.

343
00:21:01.400 --> 00:21:02.640
Please hold.

344
00:21:03.880 --> 00:21:05.640
Andrew Solomon here.

345
00:21:09.280 --> 00:21:10.720
If the sheriff was available.

346
00:21:10.880 --> 00:21:13.480
then he wasn't the one
guarding Fibonacci.

347
00:21:13.680 --> 00:21:15.320
Putnam County Sheriff's Office.

348
00:21:15.400 --> 00:21:17.720
Yeah. is. uh.
Sheriff Pronzo there?

349
00:21:17.800 --> 00:21:20.200
I'm sorry.
Sheriff Pronzo is on vacation.

350
00:21:20.600 --> 00:21:22.600
- Really?
- Yes. sir.

351
00:21:22.680 --> 00:21:24.800
There were only four
sheriffs in the county.

352
00:21:25.080 --> 00:21:27.880
And since Pronzo was the only
one who wasn't in his office.

353
00:21:27.880 --> 00:21:30.280
and his wife and kids were
waiting for him at home.

354
00:21:30.280 --> 00:21:33.240
I knew the only vacation he
was taking was with Fibonacci.

355
00:21:33.360 --> 00:21:35.840
Watching him until they
could put him in Protection.

356
00:21:36.400 --> 00:21:37.360
Thing is.

357
00:21:37.480 --> 00:21:41.000
sometimes it takes weeks for the
Marshall Service to set up a
new identity.

358
00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:44.840
So some local sheriff is stuck in
the middle of nowhere with Fibonacci.

359
00:21:45.040 --> 00:21:49.360
He gets lonely and calls home...
a lot.

360
00:21:51.360 --> 00:21:55.320
I called the phone company.
said I was Pronzo and I'd lost my bill.

361
00:21:56.080 --> 00:21:57.880
I asked for another copy.

362
00:21:59.240 --> 00:22:01.840
Seems Mrs.
Pronzo was receiving dozens of calls

363
00:22:01.920 --> 00:22:05.280
from an area code a
long way from Chicago.

364
00:22:06.320 --> 00:22:09.800
I went online.
reverse-traced the number. and voilà.

365
00:22:10.080 --> 00:22:13.440
there was Fibonacci's
exact location.

366
00:22:13.720 --> 00:22:15.040
How do you know
he's still there?

367
00:22:15.040 --> 00:22:16.960
I have someone
looking after him...

368
00:22:17.280 --> 00:22:19.560
watching from afar.
in case he moves.

369
00:22:19.680 --> 00:22:20.320
Mm-hmm.

370
00:22:23.960 --> 00:22:25.400
This is about money. isn't it?

371
00:22:25.520 --> 00:22:27.440
You're an astute man.
Mr. Falzone.

372
00:22:27.520 --> 00:22:28.120
What?

373
00:22:28.120 --> 00:22:31.360
Your friend here. John.
is trying to extort me.

374
00:22:31.440 --> 00:22:33.560
Not extortion. insurance.

375
00:22:33.760 --> 00:22:35.600
I plan on being out
of here one day.

376
00:22:35.760 --> 00:22:39.400
And I don't think my new resume's
gonna cut it in most places.

377
00:22:39.600 --> 00:22:41.720
- How much?
- $200.000.

378
00:22:42.960 --> 00:22:44.400
I'm gonna kill you.

379
00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:46.240
Quid pro quo.

380
00:22:46.320 --> 00:22:48.440
You scratch my back.
I scratch yours.

381
00:22:48.640 --> 00:22:50.840
Well. I'll give you
some quid pro quo.

382
00:22:54.960 --> 00:22:56.280
Where did you get this?

383
00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:00.320
Who took this picture?

384
00:23:00.440 --> 00:23:02.240
Well. since you took
it upon yourself

385
00:23:02.360 --> 00:23:04.640
to have some people watching over
our interests on the outside.

386
00:23:04.720 --> 00:23:08.560
we took it upon ourselves to have
some people watching over yours.

387
00:23:08.680 --> 00:23:09.920
So who's it gonna be?

388
00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:13.960
Fibonacci or your pretty
little girlfriend there?

389
00:23:23.240 --> 00:23:27.960
Yeah. you should be careful with
who visits you in here. Fish.

390
00:23:28.040 --> 00:23:29.560
These walls have eyes.

391
00:23:29.960 --> 00:23:34.360
If you touch her.
I'll kill you myself.

392
00:23:35.240 --> 00:23:37.520
One. that is an empty threat.

393
00:23:37.640 --> 00:23:39.560
You are less than a gnat to me.

394
00:23:39.640 --> 00:23:42.720
And two.
all you got to do is give me the address

395
00:23:42.800 --> 00:23:45.680
and we avoid all this
melodrama all together.

396
00:23:50.200 --> 00:23:52.200
The address. you gnat.

397
00:23:53.440 --> 00:23:54.520
Now.

398
00:23:58.520 --> 00:23:59.480
Promise me.

399
00:24:01.600 --> 00:24:03.800
Promise me it'll be
quick and painless.

400
00:24:04.680 --> 00:24:06.800
- Do you believe this guy?
- Promise me.

401
00:24:06.960 --> 00:24:10.440
The next thing that
comes out of your mouth

402
00:24:10.520 --> 00:24:12.160
that's not that address.

403
00:24:12.360 --> 00:24:16.200
there's gonna be a lot of pain...
in a lot of places.

404
00:24:27.400 --> 00:24:28.360
Canada.

405
00:24:30.840 --> 00:24:33.720
345 Hamilton Avenue.

406
00:24:34.800 --> 00:24:37.080
Thunder Bay. Ontario.

407
00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:38.440
Get out of here.

408
00:24:54.160 --> 00:24:55.320
Nice work. John.

409
00:24:57.440 --> 00:25:01.280
I guess the demise of John
Abruzzi was greatly exaggerated.

410
00:25:02.880 --> 00:25:04.720
Thank you. I appreciate it.

411
00:25:05.200 --> 00:25:08.920
Could you do me a favor and
fix this Bellick thing for me?

412
00:25:09.240 --> 00:25:10.640
Consider it done.

413
00:25:13.160 --> 00:25:14.000
Thank you.

414
00:25:14.200 --> 00:25:17.680
And Philly.
before you pull the trigger.

415
00:25:18.040 --> 00:25:20.040
look that son of a
bitch in his eyes and

416
00:25:20.160 --> 00:25:23.040
tell him John Abruzzi
said good-bye.

417
00:25:53.160 --> 00:25:57.080
"In the race toward worldwide peace and
prosperity. America will set the pace."

418
00:25:57.360 --> 00:25:58.400
"Race"?

419
00:25:58.800 --> 00:26:00.640
Rat race. Arms race.

420
00:26:00.720 --> 00:26:04.160
Can you think of a word with
a worse connotation? Fix it.

421
00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:08.280
Did you send me a baby-sitter?

422
00:26:09.720 --> 00:26:11.480
This is not the
time or the place.

423
00:26:11.640 --> 00:26:13.400
This is the time and the place.

424
00:26:13.400 --> 00:26:14.800
Don't take that tone with me.

425
00:26:14.800 --> 00:26:16.440
Remember who you
are talking to.

426
00:26:16.440 --> 00:26:18.560
I am the Vice President
of this country.

427
00:26:18.640 --> 00:26:22.600
No. actually. you're Caroline
Reynolds from Montgomery. Illinois.

428
00:26:22.960 --> 00:26:25.000
I know exactly who you are.

429
00:26:27.480 --> 00:26:28.640
Come with me.

430
00:26:36.200 --> 00:26:38.800
There is something you
need to understand.

431
00:26:38.880 --> 00:26:42.720
If you had done your job.
I never would've had to ask for Quinn.

432
00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:45.120
And there's something
you need to understand.

433
00:26:45.600 --> 00:26:49.240
You woke a sleeping beast when
you called these guys in.

434
00:26:49.360 --> 00:26:50.960
They have a bigger
agenda than any of us.

435
00:26:51.080 --> 00:26:54.160
And they get real nasty real quick
if things don't go their way.

436
00:26:54.240 --> 00:26:55.960
So now. no one is safe.

437
00:26:55.960 --> 00:26:57.000
Not you.

438
00:26:57.200 --> 00:26:58.360
Not me.

439
00:26:59.600 --> 00:27:01.160
Let's not overreact.

440
00:27:01.240 --> 00:27:05.080
I mean. I know everyone is nervous
about tomorrow. I understand that.

441
00:27:05.640 --> 00:27:08.640
But the one thing both
of us have to remember

442
00:27:08.720 --> 00:27:11.200
is that we are in
this together. okay?

443
00:27:11.480 --> 00:27:13.880
All I'm saying is these guys
are into this thing now.

444
00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:15.240
And there's no going back.

445
00:27:15.920 --> 00:27:19.360
That's bad news for everyone.

446
00:27:33.160 --> 00:27:34.720
Sebastian Balfour?

447
00:27:36.520 --> 00:27:37.200
Yeah?

448
00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:40.760
Yeah. I'm Nestor Pollack.
Midwestern Life and Casualty.

449
00:27:41.120 --> 00:27:42.840
I'm already covered. Thanks.

450
00:27:43.040 --> 00:27:45.560
Oh. no.
I'm here to discuss Veronica Donovan.

451
00:27:46.800 --> 00:27:47.480
What about her?

452
00:27:47.560 --> 00:27:49.080
Well. we've been trying
to track her down

453
00:27:49.200 --> 00:27:52.720
with respect to the property damage
from the apartment explosion.

454
00:27:52.840 --> 00:27:55.440
- Explosion?
- You didn't know.

455
00:27:55.720 --> 00:27:56.880
Oh. I'm sorry.

456
00:27:57.160 --> 00:28:01.280
It's just that her records list
you as her fiancé. So I assumed...

457
00:28:01.360 --> 00:28:02.120
Hold on.

458
00:28:02.600 --> 00:28:03.760
Is Veronica okay?

459
00:28:03.960 --> 00:28:05.480
Well. there has
been a fatality.

460
00:28:05.600 --> 00:28:06.440
Oh. my God.

461
00:28:06.560 --> 00:28:09.600
No. but the medical examiners
haven't been able to identify the...

462
00:28:09.600 --> 00:28:11.160
remains with any certainty.

463
00:28:11.360 --> 00:28:13.840
So Veronica could be okay.
we just can't find her.

464
00:28:13.920 --> 00:28:15.960
We were hoping you could help.

465
00:28:44.800 --> 00:28:45.480
Rozz.

466
00:28:48.360 --> 00:28:49.320
Reese.

467
00:28:52.480 --> 00:28:53.440
Burrows.

468
00:29:04.360 --> 00:29:06.200
Blueberry pancakes. huh?

469
00:29:06.400 --> 00:29:09.960
All right. man. you got it.
Blueberry pancakes.

470
00:29:27.280 --> 00:29:32.280
Veronica. Are you there?
If you are there. I am worried.

471
00:29:37.960 --> 00:29:39.760
I'm fine.

472
00:29:43.120 --> 00:29:45.920
Thank God. Where are you?

473
00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:53.760
Can't say. Have to go. Bye.

474
00:30:52.280 --> 00:30:53.800
345.

475
00:30:58.680 --> 00:30:59.640
This is it.

476
00:31:01.760 --> 00:31:04.080
All right. that's it. kids.
Time for bed.

477
00:31:04.160 --> 00:31:05.120
Give me a kiss.

478
00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:09.160
You okay. down there?

479
00:31:10.200 --> 00:31:11.080
Night-night.

480
00:31:12.680 --> 00:31:14.720
All right. sweetheart.
give me a kiss.

481
00:31:30.440 --> 00:31:32.640
- Kids are down.
- Thanks.

482
00:31:35.800 --> 00:31:37.920
Tonight. we send a
message. gentlemen.

483
00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:41.760
We are gonna hurt him and his
family the way he hurt ours.

484
00:32:01.520 --> 00:32:03.240
- Oh. honey?
- Yeah.

485
00:32:03.320 --> 00:32:06.480
Um. can you change the timer on the
sprinkler while you're out there?

486
00:32:06.480 --> 00:32:07.280
Oh. okay.

487
00:32:07.360 --> 00:32:09.200
- Love ya.
- Love you. too.

488
00:32:14.280 --> 00:32:15.240
Freeze!

489
00:32:17.040 --> 00:32:18.600
Police! Drop your weapon!

490
00:32:20.600 --> 00:32:21.760
I said drop it!

491
00:32:27.680 --> 00:32:28.480
Down!

492
00:32:54.160 --> 00:32:56.960
Hi. It's John.
You wanted to talk to me?

493
00:32:57.040 --> 00:32:59.040
Yeah. You hear the news?

494
00:32:59.160 --> 00:33:02.120
Falzone got popped last
night up in Canada.

495
00:33:02.320 --> 00:33:08.160
International gun charges.
Parole violation. He's in deep.

496
00:33:13.240 --> 00:33:14.880
You threw away your flowers.

497
00:33:14.960 --> 00:33:17.200
Yeah. like I said.
they don't last.

498
00:33:17.760 --> 00:33:19.560
I don't think they're dead yet.

499
00:33:21.800 --> 00:33:24.960
I don't like getting attached to
things if I know they won't last.

500
00:33:26.080 --> 00:33:27.040
There you go.

501
00:33:27.920 --> 00:33:29.760
Why are you so cynical?

502
00:33:31.280 --> 00:33:33.680
Michael. I think there's cynicism.
and then there's realism.

503
00:33:33.760 --> 00:33:36.560
And there's optimism.
hope. Faith.

504
00:33:36.640 --> 00:33:39.640
This coming from a eight-toed guy
locked away in a penitentiary.

505
00:33:39.640 --> 00:33:41.720
Mm. toes are overrated.

506
00:33:42.400 --> 00:33:45.200
Thank you for trying to make me smile.
Not today.

507
00:33:45.360 --> 00:33:48.240
- You never know.
- We're all set.

508
00:34:17.320 --> 00:34:20.680
You and I have a lot to talk about.
don't we. Fish?

509
00:34:20.760 --> 00:34:24.600
Seems Philly Falzone ran into
some problem up in Canada.

510
00:34:24.680 --> 00:34:27.560
Just because of the
information you gave him.

511
00:34:27.680 --> 00:34:28.840
What kind of trouble?

512
00:34:28.920 --> 00:34:31.680
International gun charges.
parole violation.

513
00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:34.400
He's gonna go away
for a long time.

514
00:34:34.680 --> 00:34:36.480
How'd you feel about that?

515
00:34:37.440 --> 00:34:38.520
Pretty darn good.

516
00:34:42.720 --> 00:34:45.880
- And what about PI?
- Got that back. too.

517
00:34:46.080 --> 00:34:49.520
Falzone paid Bellick yesterday.
so we're good for now.

518
00:34:49.640 --> 00:34:51.760
- It all worked out.
- Sure did.

519
00:34:51.760 --> 00:34:54.440
Nicely done.
You're a hell of an actor.

520
00:34:54.600 --> 00:34:56.040
Thank you.

521
00:34:56.360 --> 00:35:00.280
Well. this helped.
It's nice. Nice shot.

522
00:35:00.480 --> 00:35:02.000
Where did you take it?

523
00:35:02.680 --> 00:35:04.480
It's Lincoln's.
from back in the day.

524
00:35:04.600 --> 00:35:06.240
Camping trip or something.

525
00:35:06.400 --> 00:35:08.240
So. when do we get
back in that room?

526
00:35:08.640 --> 00:35:10.840
- Right away.
- Well. let's get to it.

527
00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:11.600
Yeah...

528
00:35:13.520 --> 00:35:15.520
Oh. there's one more thing.

529
00:35:18.960 --> 00:35:20.720
You are going to
give me Fibonacci

530
00:35:20.800 --> 00:35:23.200
once we're outside of
these walls. right?

531
00:35:24.440 --> 00:35:25.400
Of course.

532
00:35:29.240 --> 00:35:30.000
Thank you.

533
00:35:31.560 --> 00:35:33.760
But I think I'll keep this.

534
00:35:34.120 --> 00:35:35.280
As insurance.

535
00:35:50.320 --> 00:35:51.200
More juice?

536
00:35:51.600 --> 00:35:53.520
Why can't we have
breakfast every day?

537
00:35:53.680 --> 00:35:55.520
You should have
breakfast every day. LJ.

538
00:35:55.520 --> 00:35:56.760
It's an important meal.

539
00:35:56.960 --> 00:36:00.040
No. Why can't I have
breakfast with you every day?

540
00:36:00.120 --> 00:36:01.560
Nothing would make me happier.

541
00:36:01.760 --> 00:36:06.360
but. uh. your mommy and me--
we don't live together anymore.

542
00:36:06.440 --> 00:36:07.400
Why?

543
00:36:08.760 --> 00:36:13.160
Well. um. sometimes that happens
with mommies and daddies.

544
00:36:13.560 --> 00:36:15.960
But you know what?

545
00:36:16.120 --> 00:36:17.880
You're the luckiest
boy in the world.

546
00:36:18.040 --> 00:36:20.160
'cause your mommy
loves you very much.

547
00:36:20.560 --> 00:36:22.360
and I love you very much.

548
00:36:22.640 --> 00:36:23.800
I'll tell you what--

549
00:36:23.920 --> 00:36:25.440
how about every Sunday.

550
00:36:25.520 --> 00:36:28.400
we have our own special breakfast.
just you and me?

551
00:36:28.600 --> 00:36:29.840
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

552
00:36:30.040 --> 00:36:31.400
Little bit or a hand full?

553
00:36:31.480 --> 00:36:33.120
- Hand full.
- Hand full.

554
00:36:36.280 --> 00:36:37.320
Here we go.

555
00:36:48.360 --> 00:36:49.320
Take a walk.

556
00:36:54.880 --> 00:36:57.080
Anyone else want
to walk with him?

557
00:36:59.200 --> 00:36:59.960
Yeah.

558
00:37:03.520 --> 00:37:04.960
This is my game.

559
00:37:05.240 --> 00:37:07.560
Looks like our friend
got his throne back.

560
00:37:07.640 --> 00:37:09.080
Looks like it.

561
00:37:10.320 --> 00:37:13.760
Something tells me we may
have you to thank for that.

562
00:37:14.360 --> 00:37:16.560
- You don't want to know.
- You got that right.

563
00:37:16.640 --> 00:37:18.480
Stretch your legs. old head.

564
00:37:28.560 --> 00:37:31.120
Now. we got to have us a
lot to talk about. don't we?

565
00:37:37.960 --> 00:37:39.200
I got nothing to say.

566
00:37:40.520 --> 00:37:42.720
You think you can
play me. snowflake?

567
00:37:42.840 --> 00:37:44.360
'Cause you got college?

568
00:37:45.040 --> 00:37:47.040
Big school learnin'. huh?

569
00:37:47.240 --> 00:37:48.880
Well. let me school you.

570
00:37:49.080 --> 00:37:51.360
Darwin wins inside these walls.

571
00:37:51.760 --> 00:37:54.640
Not Einstein. Darwin.

572
00:37:54.920 --> 00:37:58.640
Yard time's over. ladies.
Let's line it up.

573
00:38:00.400 --> 00:38:02.200
I'm not done with you. Fish.

574
00:38:02.880 --> 00:38:04.880
You never even got started.

575
00:38:23.880 --> 00:38:24.640
All right.

576
00:38:28.400 --> 00:38:29.720
We're through the hard part.

577
00:38:29.840 --> 00:38:31.640
Another 18 inches.
we'll hit that pipe.

578
00:38:32.600 --> 00:38:34.440
We'll be there by Friday.

579
00:38:34.520 --> 00:38:35.680
Friday?

580
00:38:35.760 --> 00:38:37.680
Better start making
travel arrangements.

581
00:38:37.680 --> 00:38:39.400
Maricruz. here I come. baby.

582
00:38:39.520 --> 00:38:41.240
Sardinia. here I come.

583
00:38:41.320 --> 00:38:43.440
- Where are we going?
- Panama.

584
00:38:43.560 --> 00:38:45.160
- Panama.
- Panama.

585
00:38:45.640 --> 00:38:47.840
Darien Gap. South of the Canal.

586
00:38:47.960 --> 00:38:50.440
No roads.
no electricity. no cops.

587
00:38:51.520 --> 00:38:54.960
Nothing but white sand
beaches and ice cold beer.

588
00:38:55.240 --> 00:38:57.440
Well. that's nice.
but what about our lives?

589
00:38:57.560 --> 00:38:58.800
I don't know.

590
00:38:58.880 --> 00:39:00.320
We'll open a scuba shop.

591
00:39:00.440 --> 00:39:01.480
Hey. I don't dive.

592
00:39:01.560 --> 00:39:04.160
Neither do I.
but we'll have plenty of time to learn.

593
00:39:05.800 --> 00:39:06.560
Bulls.

594
00:39:12.800 --> 00:39:15.000
This con says he's
on the job in here.

595
00:39:16.240 --> 00:39:17.760
No. I don't think so.

596
00:39:17.880 --> 00:39:19.120
You heard the paisan.

597
00:39:19.200 --> 00:39:19.880
Move your ass.

598
00:39:19.880 --> 00:39:21.720
C.O.. hold on one minute.

599
00:39:28.040 --> 00:39:29.880
Now. you sure about that?

600
00:39:30.520 --> 00:39:32.920
Now. you sure you can't
use an extra hand?

601
00:39:33.040 --> 00:39:35.240
You know anything
about construction?

602
00:39:35.320 --> 00:39:38.600
Concrete is my specialty.
Can you dig it?

603
00:39:42.320 --> 00:39:45.600
- Okay. boss. Sign him up.
- You got it.

604
00:39:54.320 --> 00:39:57.560
All right. looks like Darwin
wins after all. hey. Fish?

605
00:40:04.680 --> 00:40:07.360
I have a lot of dots.
but no way to connect them.

606
00:40:07.560 --> 00:40:10.040
Nobody's getting rich here.

607
00:40:10.040 --> 00:40:11.280
What about shareholders?

608
00:40:11.400 --> 00:40:13.800
Oh. profits were minimal. and they
were all converted back to shares.

609
00:40:13.880 --> 00:40:16.560
Looks like they subcontracted out
some research and development.

610
00:40:16.560 --> 00:40:18.600
but it's pennies in the
grand scheme of things.

611
00:40:18.600 --> 00:40:20.320
Nobody was pulling
early retirement.

612
00:40:20.320 --> 00:40:23.560
You can't hide $500 million just
by moving a few decimal points.

613
00:40:23.680 --> 00:40:25.600
In a move anticipated
by many pundits.

614
00:40:25.600 --> 00:40:29.120
Vice President Reynolds announced
she is running for the Presidency.

615
00:40:29.240 --> 00:40:32.280
She made the announcement from her
hometown of Montgomery. Illinois.

616
00:40:32.280 --> 00:40:37.960
The move toward worldwide peace and
prosperity is a marathon. not a sprint.

617
00:40:38.040 --> 00:40:42.760
But I assure you.
America will be setting the pace.

618
00:40:42.960 --> 00:40:45.040
Money like that just
doesn't disappear. Nick.

619
00:40:45.160 --> 00:40:46.880
You could run a small
country with that.

620
00:40:46.880 --> 00:40:50.920
The Vice President is reported to have
the largest campaign war chest
in history.

621
00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:52.160
It is so large. in fact.

622
00:40:52.240 --> 00:40:54.560
that prognosticators
are already casting her

623
00:40:54.640 --> 00:40:56.960
as the favorite in
the presidential race.

624
00:40:57.120 --> 00:40:58.960
Maybe not a small country.

625
00:40:59.840 --> 00:41:00.880
Maybe this one.

626
